What is the difference between *git merge* and *git rebase*?
--------
The Story
-------
You and your teammate work on same project

main branch = production code

You created feature branch to add cart page
-----------------------------------------------
Current Situation

main:    A → B → C
                 ↑
            teammate added
            payment page

feature: A → B → D → E
                 ↑   ↑
            cart    checkout
            page    page
            (you)   (you)

You Finished Feature

Your manager says
"merge your feature into main"
= put your cart and checkout into production

Step 1 — Go TO Main

git checkout main

Step 2 — Bring Feature INTO Main

git merge feature

What Happens

BEFORE:
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → D → E

AFTER:
main:    A → B → C → D → E
                           ↑
                    main now has
                    cart + checkout
                    ready for production ✅
--------------------------------------------------
After git merge feature INTO main

feature: A → B → D → E        ← feature unchanged
main:    A → B → C → D → E    ← main got D and E added ✅

Now You Can Delete Feature Branch

# Feature merged into main, no longer needed
git branch -d feature

# Only main remains with full code ✅
main: A → B → C → D → E

Real World

feature branch → temporary (deleted after merge)
main branch    → permanent (always has latest code) ✅
------------------------------------------------------
What git rebase Does

git checkout feature
git rebase main

Step 1 — Feature Branch Looks at Main

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → D → E

feature says "main has C, I don't have C"
"let me put C before my D and E"

Step 2 — Temporarily Removes D and E

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B          ← D and E lifted off temporarily

Step 3 — Takes C from Main

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C      ← C added to feature

Step 4 — Puts D and E Back After C

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E  ← D and E placed after C ✅

Real World When to Use

rebase = "main has new changes, I want them in my feature branch"
         before I finish my feature

merge  = "I finished feature, put it into main"
         feature is done, going to production
--------------------------------------------------------------
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → D → E
                 
feature is missing C ⚠️
---------------------
Rebase vs Merge for This Case
---------------------
goal = get C into feature branch

git rebase main  ✅  clean, linear history
                     A→B→C→D→E

git merge main   ⚠️  works but creates extra merge commit
                     A→B→D→E→M
                     looks messy in feature branch

in this case what merge does?

What Happens

BEFORE:
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → D → E

AFTER:
main:    A → B → C            ← unchanged
feature: A → B → D → E → M   ← M created
                          ↑
                     merge commit
                     M contains C inside it
------------------------------------------
Rebase vs Merge for Same Goal

REBASE                         MERGE
feature: A→B→C→D→E             feature: A→B→D→E→M
              ↑                                  ↑
         C clearly visible          C hidden inside M
         clean history ✅           messy history ⚠️
---------------------------------------------------------
Situation

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E

you want D and E in main ✅
feature is DONE

-------
Answer — Use git merge

git checkout main
git merge feature

BEFORE:
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E

AFTER:
main:    A → B → C → D → E ✅
-------------
Simple Rule

feature missing main commits?  → rebase ✅ (during development)
main missing feature commits?  → merge  ✅ (feature is done)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In Merge When M is Created vs Not

M created (not fast forward):
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → D → E
              ↑
         feature missing C
         both branches diverged
         → M needed to combine ⚠️

No M (fast forward):
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E
              ↑
         feature has everything main has
         just moves forward
         → no M needed ✅
-----------------------------------------
What Rebase Does in This Case

Situation

main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E

goal = get D and E into main
------------
If You Do Rebase

git checkout main
git rebase feature

BEFORE:
main:    A → B → C
feature: A → B → C → D → E

AFTER:
main:    A → B → C → D → E ✅
feature: A → B → C → D → E ✅
--------------------------
Same Result as Merge!

merge result:  main = A → B → C → D → E ✅
rebase result: main = A → B → C → D → E ✅
---------------------------------
But Rebase on Main is WRONG ⚠️

NEVER rebase on main in real world

main is public branch
everyone is using main
rebase rewrites history
teammates will have conflicts ❌

----------------------------------------------
What is the difference between *git merge* and *git rebase*?

merge  = joins two branches together (creates extra commit)
rebase = moves your commits on top of another branch (clean history)

"On Top" Means

BEFORE rebase:
B is base of D and E
D and E sit on top of B

A → B → D → E
         ↑
      base of D

AFTER rebase:
C becomes new base of D and E
D and E sit on top of C

A → B → C → D → E
              ↑
         new base of D ✅
-------------------------------
Simple One Liner
-----------------------------
"on top" = your commits D and E
           now start from C
           instead of B ✅

Base of D changed from B to C — that's why it's called re-base! 🙂
-------------------------------------------------------
Simple Rule

rebase rewrites history  → never do on main ❌
merge keeps history      → safe on main ✅

Same code, new identity — that's what rebase does! 🙂
-----------------------------------------------------
What Gets Rewritten

BEFORE rebase:
D = commit hash abc123  (based on B)
E = commit hash def456  (based on D)

AFTER rebase:
D'= commit hash xyz789  (based on C) ← new hash!
E'= commit hash pqr012  (based on D')← new hash!

Same code — but different commit hash ✅
-----------------------
Why Hash Changes

Git commit hash is based on:
├── code changes
├── author
├── timestamp
└── PARENT COMMIT  ← this changes!

D was based on B → hash = abc123
D now based on C → hash = xyz789  ← parent changed so hash changes

Merge Doesn't Rewrite

MERGE:
D = abc123  ← same hash, never changes ✅
E = def456  ← same hash, never changes ✅
M = new merge commit created

REBASE:
D'= xyz789  ← new hash ⚠️
E'= pqr012  ← new hash ⚠️
no merge commit
-------------------------------------
Why Rewriting is Dangerous on Main

You have D  = abc123
Teammate has D = abc123  ← same

You rebase main
Now D'= xyz789  ← different!

Teammate still has abc123
You now have xyz789
→ Git thinks they are different commits ❌
→ causes conflicts for everyone ⚠️
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Without Rebase (direct merge, branches diverged)

git log --oneline

# M  Merge branch feature into main  ← extra commit ⚠️
# E  added checkout page
# D  added cart page
# C  payment page
# B  login page
# A  first commit

With Rebase First Then Merge (fast forward)

git log --oneline

# E  added checkout page   ← clean ✅
# D  added cart page       ← clean ✅
# C  payment page
# B  login page
# A  first commit
-----------------------------------------------
What is the difference between *git merge* and *git rebase*?

merge  = joins two branches together (creates extra commit)
rebase = rewrites commits onto another branch to create a cleaner, linear history without merge commits.

merge = copies D and E into main
        nothing moved
        nothing rewritten
        both branches keep their commits ✅

rebase = rewrites D and E as D' and E' (new hash)
         places them after C
         feature still has D' and E' ✅
         same code, new hash ✅

Starting Point

A---B---C   main
     \
      D---E   feature

git merge

git checkout main
git merge feature

Result

A---B---C---M   main
     \     /
      D---E

M created ⚠️ because main has C feature missing C branches diverged so M needed to join them

the merge commit M contains the combined result of both branches, including changes from D and E.

But D and E still remain as separate commits in history. M does not “replace” them; it just connects the two branch histories together.
------------------------

rebase takes commits like D and E and replays them on top of C, creating a straight history.

Before:

A---B---C main
     \
      D---E feature

After git rebase main:

A---B---C---D'---E'

D' and E' are rewritten versions of D and E, and no merge commit is created.






